---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="NMEA 0183">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/protocols">Protocols</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>NMEA 0183</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Protocols · Article 1 of 5</span>
        <h1>NMEA 0183</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          Open any GNSS receiver's serial port and you will almost certainly see NMEA 0183
          sentences scrolling by. Developed by the National Marine Electronics Association,
          NMEA 0183 has been the de facto standard for GNSS output since the 1980s — and despite
          its age, it remains the most universally supported format in the world.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>12 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#structure">Sentence structure</a></li>
          <li><a href="#talker-ids">Talker IDs</a></li>
          <li><a href="#checksum">Checksum</a></li>
          <li><a href="#gga">GGA — Fix data</a></li>
          <li><a href="#rmc">RMC — Recommended minimum</a></li>
          <li><a href="#gsa">GSA — DOP and active satellites</a></li>
          <li><a href="#gsv">GSV — Satellites in view</a></li>
          <li><a href="#vtg">VTG — Course and speed</a></li>
          <li><a href="#limitations">Limitations</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="structure">Sentence structure</h2>
      <p>
        Every NMEA 0183 sentence follows a strict structure. Sentences are ASCII text,
        human-readable, and terminated with a carriage return and line feed (CR+LF):
      </p>

      <div class="sentence-anatomy">
        <div class="sentence-display">$GPGGA,123519,4807.038,N,01131.000,E,1,08,0.9,545.4,M,46.9,M,,*47</div>
        <div class="sentence-parts">
          <div class="part">
            <div class="part-val">$</div>
            <div class="part-name">Start delimiter</div>
          </div>
          <div class="part">
            <div class="part-val">GP</div>
            <div class="part-name">Talker ID</div>
          </div>
          <div class="part">
            <div class="part-val">GGA</div>
            <div class="part-name">Sentence type</div>
          </div>
          <div class="part">
            <div class="part-val">,fields,</div>
            <div class="part-name">Comma-separated data fields</div>
          </div>
          <div class="part">
            <div class="part-val">*</div>
            <div class="part-name">Checksum delimiter</div>
          </div>
          <div class="part">
            <div class="part-val">47</div>
            <div class="part-name">XOR checksum (hex)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="part">
            <div class="part-val">CR LF</div>
            <div class="part-name">Terminator</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Key rules:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Maximum sentence length is <strong>82 characters</strong> (including $ and CR+LF)</li>
        <li>Fields are separated by commas. An empty field is represented by two consecutive commas (,,)</li>
        <li>All data is ASCII text — no binary values</li>
        <li>The standard baud rate is <strong>4800 bps</strong>, though modern receivers support 9600, 38400 and higher</li>
        <li>At 4800 bps, a 1 Hz update rate limits the number of sentences per cycle</li>
      </ul>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="talker-ids">Talker IDs</h2>
      <p>
        The two-character talker ID identifies which constellation or device produced the sentence.
        Multi-constellation receivers may output sentences for each constellation separately,
        or use the generic <code>GN</code> talker for combined solutions:
      </p>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Talker ID</th><th>Source</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>GP</code></td><td>GPS (USA)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GL</code></td><td>GLONASS (Russia)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GA</code></td><td>Galileo (EU)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GB</code></td><td>BeiDou (China)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GQ</code></td><td>QZSS (Japan)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>GN</code></td><td>Combined / multi-constellation (recommended for mixed solutions)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>II</code></td><td>Integrated Instrumentation (autopilot systems)</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">💡</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Practical note:</strong> A modern receiver tracking GPS, Galileo and BeiDou
          simultaneously outputs a single position fix combining all constellations. This fix
          uses the <code>GN</code> talker. Parsing software should accept both <code>GP</code>
          and <code>GN</code> talkers for all standard sentence types.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="checksum">Checksum</h2>
      <p>
        The two-character hex checksum after the <code>*</code> is computed as the XOR of all
        bytes between (but not including) <code>$</code> and <code>*</code>:
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">checksum = byte[1] XOR byte[2] XOR ... XOR byte[n]</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          Example: For $GPGGA,...*47 — XOR all bytes from 'G' through the last field character.
          Result must equal 0x47. Always validate the checksum before using data — corrupt
          sentences are common on noisy serial links.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="code-block">
        <div class="code-title">Checksum validation in Python</div>
        <pre><code>def validate_nmea(sentence):
    # Strip $ and split on *
    if not sentence.startswith('$'):
        return False
    data, checksum = sentence[1:].split('*')
    computed = 0
    for char in data:
        computed ^= ord(char)
    return computed == int(checksum, 16)</code></pre>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 - GGA -->
      <h2 id="gga">GGA — Fix data</h2>
      <p>
        GGA (Global Positioning System Fix Data) is the most important NMEA sentence —
        it contains position, fix quality, satellite count, HDOP and altitude.
        Parse GGA first for any positioning application.
      </p>

      <div class="sentence-breakdown">
        <div class="sb-sentence">$GNGGA,123519,4807.038,N,01131.000,E,1,08,0.9,545.4,M,46.9,M,,*47</div>
        <div class="sb-table">
          <div class="sb-row sb-header">
            <span>Field</span>
            <span>Value</span>
            <span>Description</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>0</span>
            <span><code>$GNGGA</code></span>
            <span>Talker ID (GN = combined) + sentence type (GGA)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>1</span>
            <span><code>123519</code></span>
            <span>UTC time — hhmmss.ss → 12:35:19 UTC</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>2–3</span>
            <span><code>4807.038,N</code></span>
            <span>Latitude — ddmm.mmm,N/S → 48°07.038' N = 48.11730° N</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>4–5</span>
            <span><code>01131.000,E</code></span>
            <span>Longitude — dddmm.mmm,E/W → 11°31.000' E = 11.51667° E</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row sb-important">
            <span>6</span>
            <span><code>1</code></span>
            <span>Fix quality: 0=no fix, 1=GPS, 2=DGPS, 4=RTK fixed, 5=RTK float, 6=estimated</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>7</span>
            <span><code>08</code></span>
            <span>Number of satellites used in fix</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>8</span>
            <span><code>0.9</code></span>
            <span>HDOP — horizontal dilution of precision</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>9–10</span>
            <span><code>545.4,M</code></span>
            <span>Altitude above mean sea level in metres</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>11–12</span>
            <span><code>46.9,M</code></span>
            <span>Geoid separation — difference between WGS84 ellipsoid and mean sea level (N)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>13</span>
            <span><code></code></span>
            <span>Age of differential corrections in seconds (empty = not using DGPS)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>14</span>
            <span><code></code></span>
            <span>DGPS reference station ID</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-warn">
        <div class="callout-icon">⚠️</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Latitude/longitude format warning:</strong> GGA encodes coordinates as
          <code>ddmm.mmmm</code> (degrees and decimal minutes), <em>not</em> decimal degrees.
          <code>4807.038</code> = 48 degrees + 07.038 minutes = 48 + 7.038/60 = <strong>48.1173°</strong>.
          This is one of the most common parsing mistakes — treating it as 48.07038° gives
          a position error of several kilometres.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 - RMC -->
      <h2 id="rmc">RMC — Recommended minimum</h2>
      <p>
        RMC (Recommended Minimum Specific GNSS Data) is the minimal sentence for navigation —
        it combines position, speed over ground, course and date in a single sentence.
        Many applications parse only RMC and GGA together.
      </p>

      <div class="sentence-breakdown">
        <div class="sb-sentence">$GNRMC,123519,A,4807.038,N,01131.000,E,022.4,084.4,230394,003.1,W*6A</div>
        <div class="sb-table">
          <div class="sb-row sb-header">
            <span>Field</span>
            <span>Value</span>
            <span>Description</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>1</span>
            <span><code>123519</code></span>
            <span>UTC time hhmmss</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row sb-important">
            <span>2</span>
            <span><code>A</code></span>
            <span>Status: A=valid, V=warning (data may be unreliable)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>3–4</span>
            <span><code>4807.038,N</code></span>
            <span>Latitude ddmm.mmm,N/S</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>5–6</span>
            <span><code>01131.000,E</code></span>
            <span>Longitude dddmm.mmm,E/W</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>7</span>
            <span><code>022.4</code></span>
            <span>Speed over ground in knots</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>8</span>
            <span><code>084.4</code></span>
            <span>Course over ground, degrees true (clockwise from north)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>9</span>
            <span><code>230394</code></span>
            <span>Date — DDMMYY → 23 March 1994</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>10–11</span>
            <span><code>003.1,W</code></span>
            <span>Magnetic variation in degrees (W = westward)</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 - GSA -->
      <h2 id="gsa">GSA — DOP and active satellites</h2>
      <p>
        GSA (GNSS DOP and Active Satellites) reports which satellites are being used in the fix
        and the dilution of precision values. One GSA sentence per constellation in multi-constellation receivers.
      </p>

      <div class="sentence-breakdown">
        <div class="sb-sentence">$GNGSA,A,3,04,05,09,12,24,36,,,,,,,1.8,1.0,1.5*20</div>
        <div class="sb-table">
          <div class="sb-row sb-header">
            <span>Field</span>
            <span>Value</span>
            <span>Description</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>1</span>
            <span><code>A</code></span>
            <span>Mode: A=automatic (2D/3D auto-select), M=manual</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row sb-important">
            <span>2</span>
            <span><code>3</code></span>
            <span>Fix type: 1=no fix, 2=2D fix, 3=3D fix</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>3–14</span>
            <span><code>04,05,09,12,24,36,...</code></span>
            <span>PRN numbers of up to 12 satellites used in the fix (empty fields = unused slots)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>15</span>
            <span><code>1.8</code></span>
            <span>PDOP — position dilution of precision</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>16</span>
            <span><code>1.0</code></span>
            <span>HDOP — horizontal dilution of precision</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>17</span>
            <span><code>1.5</code></span>
            <span>VDOP — vertical dilution of precision</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 - GSV -->
      <h2 id="gsv">GSV — Satellites in view</h2>
      <p>
        GSV (GNSS Satellites in View) provides a sky view — elevation, azimuth and signal-to-noise
        ratio for every visible satellite. Because it can carry only 4 satellites per sentence,
        multiple GSV sentences are needed when more than 4 are visible.
      </p>

      <div class="sentence-breakdown">
        <div class="sb-sentence">$GPGSV,3,1,11,03,03,111,00,04,15,270,00,06,01,010,00,13,06,292,00*74</div>
        <div class="sb-table">
          <div class="sb-row sb-header">
            <span>Field</span>
            <span>Value</span>
            <span>Description</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>1</span>
            <span><code>3</code></span>
            <span>Total number of GSV sentences in this cycle</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>2</span>
            <span><code>1</code></span>
            <span>This sentence number (1 of 3)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>3</span>
            <span><code>11</code></span>
            <span>Total satellites in view</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>4–7</span>
            <span><code>03,03,111,00</code></span>
            <span>Satellite 1: PRN=03, elevation=03°, azimuth=111°, SNR=00 dB-Hz (not tracked)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>8–11</span>
            <span><code>04,15,270,00</code></span>
            <span>Satellite 2: PRN=04, elevation=15°, azimuth=270°, SNR=00 dB-Hz</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>12–15</span>
            <span><code>06,01,010,00</code></span>
            <span>Satellite 3: PRN=06, elevation=01°, azimuth=010°, SNR=00 dB-Hz</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>16–19</span>
            <span><code>13,06,292,00</code></span>
            <span>Satellite 4: PRN=13, elevation=06°, azimuth=292°, SNR=00 dB-Hz</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">📶</div>
        <div>
          <strong>SNR interpretation:</strong> SNR (Signal-to-Noise Ratio) in GSV is measured
          in dB-Hz. A value of 0 means the satellite is visible but not tracked.
          Values of 30–40 dB-Hz indicate moderate signal strength.
          Above 40 dB-Hz is excellent. Below 25 dB-Hz the signal is marginal.
          Track 35+ dB-Hz satellites for reliable positioning.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 8 - VTG -->
      <h2 id="vtg">VTG — Course and speed</h2>
      <p>
        VTG (Course Over Ground and Ground Speed) provides velocity information.
        Less commonly parsed than GGA/RMC since RMC already includes speed and course,
        but VTG adds magnetic course and supports both knots and km/h simultaneously.
      </p>

      <div class="sentence-breakdown">
        <div class="sb-sentence">$GNVTG,054.7,T,034.4,M,005.5,N,010.2,K,A*27</div>
        <div class="sb-table">
          <div class="sb-row sb-header">
            <span>Field</span>
            <span>Value</span>
            <span>Description</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>1–2</span>
            <span><code>054.7,T</code></span>
            <span>Course over ground — 054.7° True (clockwise from true north)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>3–4</span>
            <span><code>034.4,M</code></span>
            <span>Course over ground — 034.4° Magnetic</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>5–6</span>
            <span><code>005.5,N</code></span>
            <span>Speed over ground — 5.5 knots</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row">
            <span>7–8</span>
            <span><code>010.2,K</code></span>
            <span>Speed over ground — 10.2 km/h</span>
          </div>
          <div class="sb-row sb-important">
            <span>9</span>
            <span><code>A</code></span>
            <span>Mode: A=autonomous, D=differential, E=estimated, N=not valid</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 9 - LIMITATIONS -->
      <h2 id="limitations">Limitations</h2>
      <p>
        NMEA 0183 was designed in 1983 for single-channel GPS receivers at 4800 baud.
        It shows its age in several ways:
      </p>

      <div class="limitation-list">
        <div class="limitation">
          <div class="lim-title">Bandwidth</div>
          <div class="lim-desc">
            At 4800 bps, a single GGA sentence takes ~50 ms to transmit. Outputting GGA, RMC,
            GSA and GSV at 1 Hz consumes nearly the entire available bandwidth. At 10 Hz update
            rates, 4800 bps is completely inadequate — modern high-rate applications use 115200 bps
            or higher, or switch to binary protocols entirely.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="limitation">
          <div class="lim-title">No raw measurements</div>
          <div class="lim-desc">
            NMEA carries only computed position, velocity and DOP — not pseudoranges, carrier
            phase or Doppler. Post-processing, PPP and RTK software cannot use NMEA. Raw
            measurements require binary protocols (UBX, SBF) or RINEX logging.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="limitation">
          <div class="lim-title">82-character limit</div>
          <div class="lim-desc">
            The 82-character sentence limit was designed for single-constellation, single-frequency
            receivers. Modern multi-constellation receivers produce longer data fields (more satellite
            PRNs in GSA, more GSV sentences) that strain the original format.
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="limitation">
          <div class="lim-title">No integrity information</div>
          <div class="lim-desc">
            NMEA provides DOP values but no integrity bounds — no guaranteed worst-case error.
            Safety-critical applications (aviation, autonomous driving) need integrity information
            that NMEA cannot provide. SBAS-aware sentences (GBS) partially address this.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🔄</div>
        <div>
          <strong>NMEA 2000:</strong> A newer standard (ISO 11783) using CAN bus rather than
          serial UART. Designed for marine systems. Higher bandwidth, binary encoding, network
          topology with multiple devices. Common on modern marine chart plotters and autopilots
          but not universal in general GNSS applications.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 10 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📋</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Universal but old</div>
          <div class="summary-body">NMEA 0183 is supported by virtually every GNSS receiver. ASCII, human-readable, easy to parse. Designed in 1983 — the bandwidth and raw data limitations show.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📍</div>
          <div class="summary-title">GGA is the key sentence</div>
          <div class="summary-body">GGA carries position, fix quality, satellite count, HDOP and geoid separation. Parse GGA first. Check field 6 (fix quality) before using the position.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">⚠️</div>
          <div class="summary-title">ddmm.mmmm ≠ decimal degrees</div>
          <div class="summary-body">NMEA coordinates are degrees + decimal minutes, not decimal degrees. Convert with: degrees = dd + mm.mmmm / 60. This is the most common parsing mistake.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔢</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Always validate the checksum</div>
          <div class="summary-body">XOR all bytes between $ and *. Match the two-hex-digit checksum. Discard sentences that fail. Serial links are noisy — corrupt sentences are common.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/protocols" class="nav-prev">← Protocols</a>
        <a href="/learn/protocols/rinex" class="nav-next">RINEX →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>NMEA 0183 Standard — Version 4.11. National Marine Electronics Association. <a href="https://www.nmea.org/content/STANDARDS/NMEA_0183_Standard" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">nmea.org →</a></li>
          <li>u-blox NMEA Protocol Specification. <a href="https://www.u-blox.com/sites/default/files/products/documents/u-blox8-M8_ReceiverDescrProtSpec_%28UBX-13003221%29_Public.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">u-blox →</a></li>
          <li>Trimble NMEA Reference Manual. <a href="https://www.trimble.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">trimble.com →</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

